Targets, systemd's runlevels.

Older init systems had numbered runlevels, system states like halt, multi-user text mode, and full graphical mode. Systemd's equivalent is the target, a special unit that groups other units together to define a complete system state.

A handful of targets come up regularly. The power-off target halts and powers down the machine. The rescue target is single-user mode: a root shell on the console, with no network and almost nothing running, the old runlevel one. The multi-user target is a full multi-user system with networking but no graphical interface, and it is the default on servers. The graphical target adds the desktop on top of that, and is the default on workstations. There is also a reboot target, and an emergency target, which is even more minimal than rescue, with only the root filesystem mounted and no services at all, for when things are badly broken. And the default target is simply a link pointing at whichever of these the machine boots into normally.

You manage targets with a few system-control verbs. Get-default shows which target boots by default, and set-default changes it, so you can, for instance, make a machine boot to text mode instead of graphical. Isolate switches to a target right now, dropping out of the current state into the new one. You can also reach the rescue or emergency target from the grub menu at boot time, by appending a kernel command-line option, which is invaluable when a normal boot is broken and you need a way in. For the exam, know the multi-user, graphical, rescue, and emergency targets, and the get-default, set-default, and isolate verbs. And to shut down or reboot, the modern way is system-control reboot or power-off, though the traditional shutdown command still works, including scheduling a shutdown for later with a broadcast warning.
